General topic: Sensory marketing

Current title: Sensory marketing as a solution to consumers’ unwillingness to try new products when shopping online.

Specific idea: Consumers no longer buy products alone. Instead, they search and buy experiences around purchased goods. Research shows that customers need the store atmosphere to examine and choose the products (visually pleasing stands, ability to touch the products, etc). However, much of that experience became limited due to Covid-19 restrictions, which prompted users to embrace delivered goods. This change consequently led to a more limiting customer experience. For example, consumers are less willing to try new products when shopping online, arguably because of the absence of atmospherics. Therefore, this project will assess how in-store atmospherics research can be used for delivered goods (e-commerce websites and unboxing) to improve customer experience and willingness to try new products. The findings will remain relevant after the pandemic as online shopping will become a more wide-spread habit than it was pre-pandemic.

Deliverable: A visually-pleasing paper, written in a digestible way.

1) Examine the current state of customer experience related to the delivered goods; 
2) Synthesize current research on atmospherics in offline stores, their combinations + their impact on customer experience; 
3) Determine how they can be applied to delivered goods; 
4) Discuss the implications of the findings for companies and customers (corporate social responsibility, ethics of sensory marketing).

A pivot to one/few atmospherics is possible in case the topic is too broad. For example, visuals as the most impactful atmospheric or olfactory (I have explored this one so far and found it interesting since there are many marketing agencies specializing in it).

